question:
Let $A=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
1 & 2 \\ 
3 & 4 \end{array}
\right)$ and $B=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
0 & 2 \\ 
3 & k \end{array}
\right)$.

For what value of $k$ the matrices $A$ and $B$ will be commuting?

Find $M^2+(A^T\cdot B)^{-1}$, where $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 3 & 2 \end{array}
\right)$, $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-2 & 4 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$, and $M=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
7 & 2 & 1 \\
-1 & 3 & 0  \\
2 & 0 & -2 \end{array}
\right)$.

Suppose that $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 0 & -1 \\ 
3 & 1 & 0 \\ 
-2 & 1 & 3 \end{array}
\right)$.

Find matrix $B$ such that matrices $A$ and $B$ are inverses.

Let  $A=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
1 & 3 \\ 
2 & -1 \end{array}
\right)$ and $f\left(x\right)=x^3-2x+5I_{2\times2}$. Find $f(A)$.

 Suppose that $A=\left( 
 \begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 2  & 3  \\ 
-1 & 1 & 0  \\ 
 -1 & 4 & 2 \end{array}
\right)$ and $M=\left( 
 \begin{array}{rrr}
0 & 1  & 1  \\ 
2 & 2 & 0  \\ 
0 & 3 & 2 \end{array}
\right)$. Determine $X$ knowing that $$2A-X\cdot A=M$$
